Dementia is a syndrome characterized by a progressive decline in cognitive function that interferes with a person's daily life and independence. It affects not only memory but also many other aspects of thinking and behavior.

<!--more-->

### 1. Common symptoms of dementia
- Memory loss
- Difficulties with language and communication
- Reduced understanding and knowledge of the surrounding world
- Problems with reasoning, planning, and decision-making
- Changes in personality, behavior, and emotional regulation

Dementia is not a single disease but a collection of symptoms caused by various underlying conditions. The most common types of dementia include Alzheimer's disease, vascular dementia, Lewy body dementia, and frontotemporal dementia, each affecting the brain in different ways.
